<br>
There was a Lear that recently went down because of explosive decompression but the volume of air is so different form large and small aircraft that the hole required is almost exponential.<br>
<br>
There are also specialy fabricated gun rounds that work fine on people but will not puncture the aircraft. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bantos@firionavie>Bantos</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/21/03 8:02:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=344.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Explosive Decompression.</span><hr size=1> It's a great idea to arm the pilots.  It acts more as a deterrent than anything else.  Hijackers would think twice about hijacking an airplane if they know there is a cockpit with armed men on board, not to mention the air marshalls that many flights now have.<br>
<br>
People carry guns for protection, and the same would go for pilots.  Yes, shooting out a window would be extremely bad, but I don't think that it is something that they are expecting to have to use at every flight.<br>
<br>
When a robber knows that a liquor store clerk has a shotgun behind the counter because he heard a robber got his head blown off last month for trying to rob the store, he is going to think twice.  Same for airline hijackers.<br>
<br>
If you ask me, they should go further than this by arming the flight attendants with pepper spray and the such. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=krostgutshank>Krost Gutshank</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/21/03 8:15:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=344.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Explosive Decompression.</span><hr size=1> Also, I wanted to point this out.<br>
<br>
Other then the mental effect that a firearm has on someone they are less effective in actual use in an area of close quarters, such as a plane.<br>
<br>
Make shift weapons for stabbing and slashing are cheap, easily fashioned,  more likely to get past security measures and are more effective in the close quarters of a plane than a handgun would be.<br>
<br>
In my line of work I have to regulary take a class entitled, &quot;Surviving Piercing Weapons&quot;.<br>
<br>
In the class we are shown &quot;Man with Knife&quot; vs. &quot;Man with Gun&quot; we even participate in it.<br>
<br>
Contrary to what many may think the knife guy &quot;wins&quot; an unusually LARGE percentage of the time in close quarters situations. Mostly at distances that you would likely find in scenarios on a plane.<br>
<br>
My 1st time in the course I was skeptical as were many of us but we were given the opportunity to try to &quot;shoot&quot; the knife guy before he &quot;stabbed&quot; us.<br>
<br>
Most of us were &quot;stabbed&quot; multiple times before we could  unholster the weapon and get a &quot;shot&quot; off. And we recieve regular training.<br>
<br>
Considering such a weapon is a very likely weapon for a terrorist I'd hate to see the pilot come charging and be filled with holes before he knew what happened. <br>
<br>
Then we just have happy terrorist with gun and knife.<br>
<br>
I just think there are more sensible ways of going about trying to provide better security and safety for passengers.<br>
<br>
<br>
