Blood <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dashanvaliant>DashanValiant</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 83<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/21/03 4:53:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=344.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Deterring Hijackers</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If they feel that this will prevent them from completing their attack and just them dieing then it could possibly act as a deterrent<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Perhaps.  I would say though, you should concentrate on coming up with ways to defeat, not deter.  I have a respect for the power of monomania.  I do not believe you can scare someone who is willing to die by the simple thought that they might not succeed.  If you can practically guarantee failure, then you deter all but the most desperate.  But simply putting a gun on a plane does not do this.  Honestly, beyond the <br>
complete cut-off of the cockpit from rest of plane, I don't know how you could guarantee failure.  And that apparently has its own problems.<br>
<br>
Really, the most effective thing towards anti-hijacking of planes was the success.  Previously, when planes where hijacked, generally, it meant the passengers went somewhere they didn't want to go.  Spent a while somewhere else, and then eventually got back and were, except in rare cases, unharmed.  Now, however, anyone on a hijacked plane is going to assume they are going to die unless they do something.  The &quot;sit quietly in your seat until it is over&quot; days are gone.  <br>
<br>
<br>
